{
    "id": "electronics/light-sensor",
    "title": "Build a Light Sensor",
    "description": "Use a photoresistor and Arduino to measure ambient brightness.",
    "image": "/assets/quests/basic_circuit.svg",
    "npc": "/assets/npc/orion.jpg",
    "start": "start",
    "dialogue": [
        {
            "id": "start",
            "text": "Hey again! Orion here. Let's build a light sensor. Work on a non-conductive surface, wear safety goggles and an anti-static wrist strap, discharge static by touching grounded metal, keep hands dry, and unplug the board before wiring to avoid shorts.",
            "options": [{ "type": "goto", "goto": "materials", "text": "What do I need?" }]
        },
        {
            "id": "materials",
            "text": "Gather one Arduino Uno, a breadboard, three jumper wires, one photoresistor, one 10 kΩ resistor, one USB cable, a digital multimeter, safety goggles, an anti-static wrist strap, and a laptop with the Arduino IDE installed. Keep components in a tray so leads don't touch or short.",
            "options": [
                {
                    "type": "process",
                    "process": "arduino-ide-install",
                    "text": "Install the Arduino IDE"
                },
                {
                    "type": "goto",
                    "goto": "wire",
                    "text": "Ready to wire!",
                    "requiresItems": [
                        { "id": "72b4448e-27d9-4746-bd3a-967ff13f501b", "count": 1 },
                        { "id": "d1105b87-8185-4a30-ba55-406384be169f", "count": 1 },
                        { "id": "3cd82744-d2aa-414e-9f03-80024b624066", "count": 3 },
                        { "id": "6301ff22-49c9-468b-88aa-cafedfd5dcd3", "count": 1 },
                        { "id": "ffe0b74a-f111-4d66-b4c3-d82965a976ac", "count": 1 },
                        { "id": "fb60696a-6c94-4e5e-9277-b62377ee6d73", "count": 1 },
                        { "id": "5127e156-3009-4db4-85ac-e3ea070b68f2", "count": 1 },
                        { "id": "c9b51052-4594-42d7-a723-82b815ab8cc2", "count": 1 },
                        { "id": "d30d7a65-bd11-42a2-89c1-2828e990a3b2", "count": 1 },
                        { "id": "b6fc1ed6-f399-4fdb-9f9d-3913f893f43d", "count": 1 }
                    ]
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "wire",
            "text": "Disconnect the USB cable. Build a voltage divider by connecting one leg of the photoresistor to 5 V and the other to one side of the 10 kΩ resistor, then connect the resistor's far leg to GND. Measure the photoresistor's resistance in ambient light with the multimeter, run a jumper from the junction to A0, keep your goggles on, and make sure no bare wires touch before powering up.",
            "options": [
                {
                    "type": "goto",
                    "goto": "code",
                    "text": "Wired up and measured.",
                    "process": "measure-photoresistor",
                    "requiresItems": [
                        { "id": "5127e156-3009-4db4-85ac-e3ea070b68f2", "count": 1 },
                        { "id": "6301ff22-49c9-468b-88aa-cafedfd5dcd3", "count": 1 },
                        { "id": "c9b51052-4594-42d7-a723-82b815ab8cc2", "count": 1 }
                    ]
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "code",
            "text": "Plug the USB cable back in and upload a sketch that reads A0 and prints to the serial monitor. Shade and expose the sensor to watch the values shift. Avoid pointing lasers at the sensor and don't stare into bright lamps during testing.",
            "options": [{ "type": "goto", "goto": "finish", "text": "Numbers are changing!" }]
        },
        {
            "id": "finish",
            "text": "Nice work! Unplug the board before making changes, coil the USB cable, and store all parts for future builds.",
            "options": [{ "type": "finish", "text": "Cool!" }]
        }
    ],
